611|## [04:10 KST] Diffusive in Plain Sight: An Inconspicuous Law of Market Impact
612|- **URL**: https://arxiv.org/abs/2606.07059
613|- **Source Type**: paper
614|- **Domain**: microstructure
615|- **Trading Relevance**: 8
616|- **Time Horizon**: swing
617|- **Actionability**: study
618|- **Henry Risk Link**: execution | sizing
619|- **Why it matters**: Bonart (2026) derives the square-root law of market impact from first principles — by requiring that both realized and counterfactual returns be diffusive. The paper shows that the square-root law emerges naturally in the information-neutral regime, while a crossover to linear impact occurs under strong informational coupling. Critically, cumulative market impact is itself diffusive in the weak-coupling regime — a diagnostic that many popular impact models (propagator models, latent liquidity models) fail to satisfy. This is a theoretical justification for the impact models underlying execution algorithms.
620|- **Raw excerpt / abstract**: "Decomposing impact as the difference between realized and counterfactual returns and requiring both to be diffusive yields an identity that restricts admissible impact scaling at the level of individual participants. This constraint implies the square-root law in the information-neutral regime and a crossover to linear impact under strong informational coupling, consistent with empirical observations. In the weak-coupling regime, cumulative market impact is itself diffusive."
621|- **Cold read**: This establishes the theoretical validity of the square-root law (impact proportional to sqrt(order size)) as a first-principles constraint, not just an empirical fit. The informational coupling regime-shift (square root → linear) is important: when the market knows your trade has information content, impact is linear in order size — much more expensive. This means the execution-cost penalty for trading on perceived information is even larger than the standard models predict.
622|- **Trading insight**: The regime-shift insight matters for Henry's execution: when MSTR or BTC is in play on material news, the impact regime switches from square-root (cheap, informational neutral) to linear (expensive, info content priced). This means post-news execution is disproportionately costly. The practical implication: if you need to trade around news events (FOMC, earnings, BTC ETF flow data), the optimal execution window is before the news when impact is square-root, not after when it becomes linear. The paper provides theoretical backing for what experienced traders already sense — but now with a mathematical proof.
623|- **Change sensor**: (1) Do execution algos publish their impact model choice (square-root vs linear)? (2) Can real-time impact regime detection be implemented using the diffusive diagnostic? (3) Is the regime shift observable in on-chain perp data (Hyperliquid)?
624|- **Follow-up question**: For MSTR specifically — does the NAV premium/discount regime affect the impact regime? (i.e., when MSTR trades at a premium, is the effective liquidity deeper = square-root, and at a discount, is it shallower = linear?)
