641|## [04:10 KST] Beyond Agent Architecture: Reproducibility Crisis in LLM Trading Systems
642|- **URL**: https://arxiv.org/abs/2606.08285
643|- **Source Type**: paper
644|- **Domain**: cognition | ai-world-sensing | execution
645|- **Trading Relevance**: 10
646|- **Time Horizon**: swing
647|- **Actionability**: monitor
648|- **Henry Risk Link**: sizing | execution | FOMO
649|- **Why it matters**: Yao & Zheng (2026) conduct the first systematic audit of execution realism in LLM-based trading research — covering 30 primary studies. The findings are damning: studies vary wildly in data provenance, temporal split discipline, execution timing, turnover treatment, and transaction-cost modeling. Architecture reporting is generally clearer than the evaluation assumptions needed to judge whether a trading result is economically interpretable or reproducible. A 10-equity worked example shows that explicit friction and timing choices can materially compress active-strategy results. This directly applies to Henry's own ATLAS trading system — the paper's critique of execution realism is the most relevant audit framework available.
650|- **Raw excerpt / abstract**: "Across the audited sample, architecture reporting is generally clearer than the evaluation assumptions needed to judge whether a trading result is economically interpretable or reproducible. A 10-equity worked example is included only as a methodological scaffold to illustrate how explicit friction and timing choices can materially compress active-strategy results. The main conclusion is that the next useful step for LLM trading research is not only better agent design, but also clearer reporting standards for execution realism, reproducibility, and evaluation comparability."
651|- **Cold read**: This should be required reading for anyone building LLM-based trading systems — including Henry. The paper provides a coded evidence matrix assessing point-in-time controls, split transparency, held-out evaluation, cost/turnover treatment, execution semantics, universe definition, and artifact release. Most published LLM trading results are not reproducible and would not survive real-world execution costs. The "10-equity worked example" showing how friction compresses results is a direct warning.
652|- **Trading insight**: Henry should apply the paper's audit framework to his own ATLAS system: (a) are backtests point-in-time? (b) is execution cost modeled conservatively? (c) is turnover/spill cost captured? (d) is the evaluation truly out-of-sample? This reframes how to evaluate ATLAS — not just raw returns, but audit score on the Yao-Zheng evidence matrix. The paper's 10-equity worked example should be replicated as a benchmark before ATLAS is trusted with real capital.
653|- **Change sensor**: (1) Does the LLM trading research community adopt the paper's reporting standards? (2) Can Henry's ATLAS audit against this framework? (3) Do any new LLM trading papers cite and apply this method as a baseline?
654|- **Follow-up question**: What would Henry's ATLAS score on each dimension of the Yao-Zheng evidence matrix, and what are the weakest dimensions?
