694|- **Why it matters**: The 1,000x cost collapse in AI inference (from $20/M tokens in late 2022 to $0.40/M in 2026) represents one of the fastest cost declines in computing history — faster than the transistor cost curve or the Moore's Law trajectory. This is not a single factor but a multiplicative compound of hardware (H100→Blackwell 2-3x), software (vLLM, SGLang boosting utilization from 30% to 80%), model architecture (MoE, 3-5x savings), and quantization (INT8/INT4, 2-4x). Inference now accounts for 2/3 of all AI compute demand, up from 1/3 in 2023. GPU operators optimizing for inference earn 20-40% more revenue per GPU-hour than those serving raw compute.
695|- **Raw excerpt / abstract**: "In late 2022, running a GPT-4-class model cost approximately $20 per million tokens. In early 2026, equivalent performance costs $0.40 per million tokens — or less. That is a 1,000x reduction in just over three years... Inference accounts for approximately two-thirds of all AI compute demand, up from roughly one-third in 2023."
696|- **Cold read**: The inference cost collapse is the most important structural shift in AI economics. Two implications: (1) the Jevons paradox — cheaper inference drives more demand, not less, so GPU demand continues growing even as per-token costs fall; (2) the value chain shifts from model training to inference serving. Companies positioned at the inference layer (GPU marketplaces, optimized inference hardware) benefit disproportionately. This reinforces the bull case for datacenter infrastructure but challenges the premium valuations of pure-play training companies.
697|- **Trading insight**: For Henry's world-sensing: the inference cost collapse means agent-based workflows (multi-step reasoning, tool use) become economically viable at scale. Agents generating 10,000+ tokens per task at $0.40/M tokens cost $0.004 per task — negligible. This is the economic foundation for the agent economy thesis clipped in earlier runs. The structural question: which companies capture the value from cheaper inference? NVIDIA (GPU demand grows via Jevons paradox), inference-optimized hardware (Groq, custom ASICs), or hyperscalers who bundle inference with cloud services?
